# Desktop & CLI Patterns

**Capability test:** Skip this file unless the task targets a desktop or CLI codebase.

Coding patterns for desktop applications (Electron, Tauri, native) and CLI tools. IF your project is a desktop app or CLI, apply these patterns.

All numeric values (timings, sizes) in this file are [DEFAULT] - adjust per project.

---

## PART 1: DESKTOP APPLICATIONS

---

### Architecture

```
Desktop App Architecture (typical for Electron/Tauri-style apps - adapt to your framework):

Main Process (Native Shell):
  - Window management (create, resize, position, close)
  - System tray integration
  - Native menus
  - File system access
  - System notifications
  - Auto-updater
  - IPC bridge to renderer

Renderer (UI Process):
  - Full web frontend (follows all web rules from frontend.md and ui-design-system.md)
  - Communicates with main process via IPC only
  - NO direct access to system APIs from the renderer (security boundary)
```

### Window Management

```
Rules:
  - Remember window size and position on close -> restore on next launch
  - Respect minimum window size (don't let app become unusable)
  - Minimum: [DEFAULT] 800x600 for feature apps, [DEFAULT] 400x300 for utilities
  - Support multiple windows where it makes sense (settings in separate window)
  - Properly handle display changes (monitor disconnect, DPI change)
  - Graceful close: prompt to save unsaved work before quitting
```

### Native Menu Bar (IF your app has a menu bar)

Not all desktop apps need a full menu bar (kiosks, single-purpose utilities, games may skip or customize). IF your app uses a native menu bar:

**Rules:**
- **Follow platform conventions** - macOS: app name menu with Preferences and Quit; Windows/Linux: File menu typically first
- **Platform-standard keyboard shortcuts** - don't override Cmd+C, Cmd+V, Cmd+Q, etc.
- **Include only relevant menus** - a document-based app needs File (New/Open/Save); a dashboard app may not
- **Every menu item has a keyboard shortcut** where applicable
- **Disable menu items** when not applicable (gray out, don't hide)
- **Edit menu** should always include Undo/Redo, Cut/Copy/Paste, Find (these are user expectations on desktop)
- **Help menu** with documentation link and version info

### System Tray

```
When to use:
  - App runs in background (background tasks, monitoring, sync)
  - Quick-access actions without opening main window
  - Status indication (connected/disconnected, sync status)

Tray menu:
  ├── Open {App Name}
  ├── Status: Connected yes
  ├── ─────────────
  ├── Preferences
  ├── Check for Updates
  ├── ─────────────
  └── Quit

Rules:
  - Tray icon changes to reflect status (active, syncing, error)
  - Click on tray icon: show/hide main window (macOS: show menu)
  - Right-click: always show context menu
  - Minimize to tray option (configurable in settings)
  - Show badge count on tray icon (if app has notifications)
```

### Auto-Updates (IF your app supports self-updating)

```
Flow:
  1. Check for updates on launch (silent, background)
  2. Check periodically (every 6 hours)
  3. If update available: show non-intrusive notification ("Update available")
  4. User clicks "Update" -> download in background with progress
  5. When ready: "Restart to update" button (don't force-restart)
  6. On next launch: apply update -> show "What's new" changelog

Rules:
  - Avoid force-updating while user is working - notify and let them choose when. Exception: regulated environments with MDM may require forced security updates.
  - Avoid auto-restarting without user consent
  - Show download progress
  - Allow "Skip this version" for non-critical updates
  - Critical security updates: more prominent notification, but still don't force
  - Sign all updates (code signing) - never distribute unsigned binaries
```

### IPC (Inter-Process Communication)

```
Rules:
  - Define ALL IPC channel names as constants in a shared file
  - Renderer should not directly call Node.js APIs - use IPC. Exception: preload scripts with controlled `contextBridge` exposure for specific APIs.
  - Validate all IPC payloads on both sides
  - Use typed IPC (type-safe channel -> payload mapping)
  - Minimize data transferred over IPC (don't send entire files, send paths)
  - Handle IPC errors gracefully (main process crashed, channel not found)
```

**Principle:** IPC channels follow a consistent naming convention so both processes can discover and validate messages.

[REFERENCE] Common IPC channel naming patterns:

```
Channel naming:
  {domain}:{action}

  file:open
  file:save
  file:export
  settings:get
  settings:set
  update:check
  update:install
  window:minimize
  window:close
```

### Desktop-Specific UX

- **Drag and drop** for files: support dropping files onto the app window
- **Native dialogs** for file open/save (not custom file pickers)
- **Right-click context menus** on relevant elements
- **Keyboard shortcuts** for all common actions (display in menu + tooltips)
- **Multi-select** in lists (Shift+click for range, Cmd/Ctrl+click for individual)
- **Undo/Redo** for destructive actions (Cmd/Ctrl+Z)
- **Clipboard integration** - copy/paste works everywhere as expected
- **Window title** reflects current context ("{Current View} - {App Name}")
- **Loading indicator** in window title bar or status bar for background operations

